lights the humanistic nature of information practices and concepts by thinking through key terms. It describes and anticipates directions for how the humanities can contribute to our understanding of information from a range of theoretical, historical, and global perspectives. Together with Information: A Reader, it sets forth a major humanistic vision of the concept of information.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aInformation sciencexMiscellanea. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAbel, Jonathan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbel, Jonathan E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCasetti, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrederick, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrederick, Samuel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGeoghegan, Bernard Dionysius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayles, N. Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelton, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorodowich, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Jeremy David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJordan, Matthew F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennerly, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennerly, Michele, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKittler, Wolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLupton, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4htt